data.name: dragonsLairLabel.Text
data.value: Dragon Lair —Dragon Tile This tile is used to delay a dragon’s movement. The Dragon Lair is placed on top of a dragon and prevents that dragon from moving or activating tiles this turn. Remove the Dragon Lair from the game at the end of the turn.

data.name: dragonBreathLabel.Text
data.value: Dragon Breath —Dragon Tile This tile is used to remove tiles in play before the dragons move. The Dragon Breath is placed on top of a dragon, and any tiles in the four squares adjacent to the dragon are destroyed. Remove the destroyed tiles and the Dragon Breath from the game after both players have placed tiles, and before moving the dragons.

data.name: lotusPondLabel.Text
data.value: Lotus Pond — Proximity Tile The lotus pond is used to pull a dragon. When a dragon moves into one of the lotus pond’s eight squares of influence and is not facing directly away from the lotus pond, the dragon is drawn one square closer. If a dragon is drawn into or moves into the same square as the lotus pond, the tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn. Dragons cannot be pulled backwards.

data.name: lotusFlowerLabel.Text
data.value: Lotus Flower —Proximity Tile The lotus flower is used to pull a dragon. When a dragon moves into one of the lotus flower’s two squares of influence and is not facing directly away from the lotus flower, the dragon is drawn one square closer. If a dragon is drawn into or moves into the same square as the lotus flower, the tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn. Dragons cannot be pulled backwards.

data.name: stormLabel.Text
data.value: Storm — Proximity Tile The storm is used to blow a dragon off course, or to propel a dragon forward. When a dragon moves into one of the storm’s eight squares of influence and is not facing directly toward the storm, the dragon is pushed one square further away from the storm. If a dragon moves into the same square as the storm, the tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn. Dragons cannot be pushed backwards.

data.name: windLabel.Text
data.value: Wind — Proximity Tile The wind is used to blow a dragon off course, or to propel a dragon forward. When a dragon moves into one of the wind’s two squares of influence and is not facing directly toward the wind, the dragon is pushed one square further away. If a dragon moves into the same square as the wind, the tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn. Dragons cannot be pushed backwards.

data.name: wildfireLabel.Text
data.value: Wildfire —Proximity Tile The wildfire is used to ward off approaching dragons. When a dragon moves into one of the wildfire’s two squares of influence and is facing in a proper direction, the dragon is drawn around the tile, and turned 180-degrees. The dragon is considered to have entered only the squares in which it began and ended the movement caused by the wildfire. If a dragon moves into the same square as the wildfire, the tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn.

data.name: watchfireLabel.Text
data.value: Watchfire —Proximity Tile The watchfire is used to ward off approaching dragons. When a dragon moves into one of the watchfire’s two squares of influence and is facing in a proper direction, the dragon is drawn around the tile, and turned 90-degrees. The dragon is considered to have entered only the squares in which it began and ended the movement caused by the watchfire. If a dragon moves into the same square as the watchfire, the tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn.

data.name: tripleRiverLabel.Text
data.value: Three Rivers —Impact Tile The three rivers are used to turn a dragon 90-degrees or move it down stream. The dragon will move through the river and exit out of the waterfall side of the tile. Three sides of the river tile are approachable. If a dragon moves into the river tile’s square from the single unapproachable side, or if a dragon enters the river with its side, the river tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn.

data.name: doubleRiverLabel.Text
data.value: Two Rivers — Impact Tile The two rivers are used to turn a dragon 90-degrees. The dragon will move through the river and exit out of the waterfall side of the tile. The two river sides of the tile are approachable. If a dragon moves into the river tile’s square from one of the two unapproachable sides, or if a dragon enters the river with its side, the river tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn.

data.name: singleRiverLabel.Text
data.value: Single River — Impact Tile The single river is used to accelerate a dragon. The dragon will move through the river tile into the next square. Both sides of the single river are approachable. If a dragon moves into the single river tile’s square from one of the two unapproachable sides, or if a dragon enters the river with its side, the river tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn.

data.name: monkLable.Text
data.value: Monk — Impact Tile The monk is used to ward off a dragon from any direction. This tile turns the dragon 180-degrees and deflects it in the opposite direction. All four sides of the monk are approachable. If a dragon hits the monk with its side, the monk tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn.

data.name: samuraiLabel.Text
data.value: Samurai —Impact Tile The samurai is used to deflect the dragon off the samurai’s shield. This tile turns the dragon 90- degrees and propels it forward into the square adjacent to the samurai. The two shield sides of the samurai are approachable. If a dragon approaches the samurai from one of the two unprotected sides, or if a dragon hits the samurai with its side, the samurai tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn.

data.name: roninLabel.Text
data.value: Ronin — Impact Tile The ronin are used to deflect a dragon off either one of their shields. This tile turns the dragon 180- degrees and deflects it in the opposite direction. The two shield sides of the ronin are approachable. If a dragon approaches the ronin from one of the two unprotected sides, or if a dragon hits the ronin with its side, the ronin tile is destroyed and removed from the game at the end of the turn.
